  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is it too late to start a computer science degree if I am 20 and don't know any programming languages?",
  "response": "No, it is not too late to start a computer science degree at 20, even if you don't know any programming languages. In fact, 20 is a great age to begin! Many people start their college education or switch fields at this time or even later, and computer science is a field that welcomes learners of all ages.\n\nHere\u2019s why it\u2019s not too late:\n\n1. **Foundational Learning**: Computer science programs are designed to start from the basics. You\u2019ll typically take introductory courses in programming, logic, and problem-solving, which are geared toward beginners.\n\n2. **Age is Not a Barrier**: Many students start their degrees later or return to school after exploring other paths. You\u2019re still very young in terms of career development, and you have plenty of time to learn and grow.\n\n3. **Programming is Learnable**: While knowing a programming language can be helpful, it\u2019s not a requirement for starting a computer science degree. You\u2019ll learn languages like Python, Java, or C++ as part of your coursework.\n\n4. **Career Opportunities**: The demand for computer science professionals is high and continues to grow. Starting now gives you time to build solid skills and position yourself for a rewarding career in tech.\n\n5. **Self-Paced Learning**: Outside of your degree program, there are countless free and paid resources online to help you learn programming and computer science concepts at your own pace.\n\n### Tips to Get Started:\n- **Practice Coding**: Start with beginner-friendly languages like Python or JavaScript using free platforms like Codecademy, freeCodeCamp, or Khan Academy.\n- **Explore Computer Science Basics**: Familiarize yourself with concepts like algorithms, data structures, and problem-solving.\n- **Set a Study Routine**: Consistency is key when learning something new, especially programming.\n- **Join Communities**: Engage with online forums, coding groups, or local meetups to connect with others and learn from their experiences.\n\nRemember, many successful programmers and computer scientists started later in life or switched careers. What matters most is your passion, dedication, and willingness to learn. You\u2019re absolutely not behind!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
